{
  "stem": "20089.1",
  "chunk_idx": 1,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 8.2,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 8,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 11,
      "text": "There was some-- some way that one could get people to come to South Africa.",
      "word_count": 15
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 8,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 12,
      "text": "And he went back to-- to Johannesburg.",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 8,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 13,
      "text": "And about six months later, my father announced that he had got the right papers and he was going to Johannesburg, and as soon as he could, he would bring the family to Johannesburg.",
      "word_count": 34
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 8,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 14,
      "text": "He left in 1927.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 8,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 15,
      "text": "And in 1929, we arrived in South Africa, in Johannesburg.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 9,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "My mother and my sister.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 9,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "And my first real memory is Johannesburg.",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 9,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And in fact, Johannesburg, where my mother pushed me into school because she had to start working.",
      "word_count": 17
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 9,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "And I went to [?",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 9,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "Dorfintine ?] School, which was a school where all the immigrant children were going.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 9,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "And we had an Afrikaans teacher who used to say, [AFRIKAANS] which means stand up, donkeys, sit down, donkeys.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 9,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "I don't think she really understood the traumas that the immigrants were going through.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 10,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "Three or four.",
      "word_count": 3
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 10,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "But my mother pushed me into school, and said that I was six.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 10,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "That was the starting age of the children.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 10,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "But I definitely wasn't six.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 10,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "I was probably four or five.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 11,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "What I do remember, which I really wasn't very happy about, was that my mother and father, particularly my mother, loved to ingratiate herself with the teachers by bringing them wine on Pesach-- and none of them were Jewish-- and matzoh.",
      "word_count": 41
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 11,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "And when they came to the school, I would run away and pretend that they weren't my parents-- weren't my mother.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 11,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "And I think I envied the girls who were, as I called, [NON-ENGLISH], which means that they were born in South Africa and they had parents who could talk English.",
      "word_count": 30
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 11,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "My parents, of course, spoke with an accent, and it was embarrassing for me.",
      "word_count": 14
    }
  ],
